docs.abstract: After state lawmakers voted to extend minimum-wage and other protections to independent contractors, Uber said it would not treat its drivers as employees.
docs.snippet: After state lawmakers voted to extend minimum-wage and other protections to independent contractors, Uber said it would not treat its drivers as employees.
docs.lead_paragraph: SAN FRANCISCO — After months of bickering over who would be covered by a landmark bill meant to protect workers, California legislators passed legislation on Wednesday that could help hundreds of thousands of independent contractors become employees and earn a minimum wage, overtime pay and other benefits.

headline.main: California’s Contractor Law Stirs Confusion Beyond the Gig Economy
headline.print_headline: Gig-Worker Law Sows Confusion and Defiance

byline.original: By Kate Conger and Noam Scheiber

docs.abstract: The tide has turned for Forever 21 and similar fashion retailers in the past few years. Its hundreds of stores are getting less foot traffic, especially among the young and fashion-forward.
docs.snippet: The tide has turned for Forever 21 and similar fashion retailers in the past few years. Its hundreds of stores are getting less foot traffic, especially among the young and fashion-forward.
docs.lead_paragraph: Forever 21, the fast-fashion retailer that spread its gospel of $5 shirts and $15 dresses from Southern California to hundreds of malls around the world, is preparing to file for bankruptcy in the coming weeks, according to three people with knowledge of its plans.

headline.main: Forever 21, Losing Young Shoppers, Is Said to Be Near Bankruptcy Filing
headline.print_headline: Retailer of Youth Fashion Is Said to Be Near Bankruptcy Filing

byline.original: By Sapna Maheshwari and Michael Corkery

docs.abstract: As tech companies try to make amends with publishers, Google changes its search engine to address an old complaint.
docs.snippet: As tech companies try to make amends with publishers, Google changes its search engine to address an old complaint.
docs.lead_paragraph: After weeks of reporting, a journalist breaks a story. Moments after it goes online, another media organization posts an imitative article recycling the scoop that often grabs as much web traffic as the original.

headline.main: Google Says a Change in Its Algorithm Will Highlight ‘Original Reporting’
headline.print_headline: Google to Put Originators Of News At the Top

docs.abstract: The company’s parent has been trying to rescue the public offering amid concerns about the high valuation for a business that is deeply unprofitable.
docs.snippet: The company’s parent has been trying to rescue the public offering amid concerns about the high valuation for a business that is deeply unprofitable.
docs.lead_paragraph: WeWork, the shared office space giant, gained the backing of some of the world’s top investors, but it received a much colder reception when it tried to sell its shares on Wall Street.

headline.main: WeWork Delays I.P.O. After Chilly Reception From Investors
headline.print_headline: With Investors Unimpressed, an Unprofitable WeWork Delays Its I.P.O.

byline.original: By Michael J. de la Merced and Peter Eavis

docs.abstract: The software giant said a week before its annual conference that Mr. Hurd, one of its two chief executives, would step away.
docs.snippet: The software giant said a week before its annual conference that Mr. Hurd, one of its two chief executives, would step away.
docs.lead_paragraph: SAN FRANCISCO — Oracle said Wednesday that Mark Hurd, one of two chief executives at the big software company, would take a leave of absence to address undisclosed medical issues.

headline.main: Oracle C.E.O. Mark Hurd Is Taking a Medical Leave
headline.print_headline: Oracle Chief Is Taking a Medical Leave

docs.abstract: The bank announced measures to stimulate eurozone growth, but will face questions about what else it can do if the economy fails to respond.
docs.snippet: The bank announced measures to stimulate eurozone growth, but will face questions about what else it can do if the economy fails to respond.
docs.lead_paragraph: FRANKFURT — The European Central Bank took unexpectedly aggressive steps on Thursday to head off a downturn before it gained momentum, but the bank signaled that it was reaching the limits of what it could do to stimulate the eurozone economy.

headline.main: E.C.B. Acts to Head Off Recession Threat in Europe, With a Caveat
headline.print_headline: E.C.B. Fights Recession, But Signals It Needs Help

docs.abstract: Days after the city declared it a terrorist organization, the National Rifle Association took action against San Francisco.
docs.snippet: Days after the city declared it a terrorist organization, the National Rifle Association took action against San Francisco.
docs.lead_paragraph: The National Rifle Association sued San Francisco on Monday, less than a week after the city’s board of supervisors declared the group a terrorist organization and moved to limit relationships with companies that do business with the N.R.A.

headline.main: N.R.A. Files Suit Against San Francisco

docs.abstract: From Washington to London. From the price of avocados to Amazon Prime. Here’s how Joseph Plambeck, deputy tech editor, rides herd on how tech is changing the way we live.
docs.snippet: From Washington to London. From the price of avocados to Amazon Prime. Here’s how Joseph Plambeck, deputy tech editor, rides herd on how tech is changing the way we live.
docs.lead_paragraph: How do New York Times journalists use technology in their jobs and in their personal lives? Joseph Plambeck, deputy technology editor in New York, discussed the tech he’s using.

headline.main: Staying on Top of Tech’s Changing Story
headline.print_headline: Keeping Pace With Tech’s Changing Story

docs.abstract: The U.S. has never cut interest rates below zero, but such a move has been considered. There are some big hurdles.
docs.snippet: The U.S. has never cut interest rates below zero, but such a move has been considered. There are some big hurdles.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — The world has gone topsy-turvy. President Trump invited, and then disinvited, the Taliban to Camp David. Taylor Swift is in a long-term relationship, and Popeyes put its fried chicken on a bun. Now Mr. Trump wants the Federal Reserve to join everyone else in the upside down that is 2019.

headline.main: Trump Wants Negative Rates. Here’s How That Would Work.

docs.abstract: In 2019 in the U.S., sport utility vehicles and pickups are grabbing a record 70 percent of the market. Asian and European automakers see things differently.
docs.snippet: In 2019 in the U.S., sport utility vehicles and pickups are grabbing a record 70 percent of the market. Asian and European automakers see things differently.
docs.lead_paragraph: The humble family sedan was once inseparable from American culture, the prime mover of suburban commutes and summer road trips. But most Detroit automakers are ridding their lineups of sedans and diverting investment to S.U.V.s and crossovers, not to mention electric vehicles and self-driving tech.

headline.main: S.U.V. vs. Sedan, and Detroit vs. the World, in a Fight for the Future
headline.print_headline: American Sedans Face a Bleak Future
